        <name>8.2.1.5 Exercise 1 2x2 linear system inverse matrix method</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; Solve the following linear system of equations using the inverse matrix method:
&lt;span class="math display"&gt;\[\begin{matrix}
{@a@} x_1 &amp;amp; + &amp;amp; {@b@} x_2 &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; {@y[1, 1]@} \\
{@c@} x_1 &amp;amp; + &amp;amp; {@d@} x_2 &amp;amp; = &amp;amp; {@y[2, 1]@} \\
\end{matrix}\]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt; \(x =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;We first check if \(A \) is invertible by, for instance, computing the determinant. Since \[ \det A = {@determinant(A)@} \neq 0, \] A is invertible. From the equation \(Ax = b\), since \(A \) is invertible, we can obtain the solution using \(x = A^{-1}Ax
    = A^{-1}b\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We compute \(A^{-1} = {@Ainv@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;Finally we find \(x = A^{-1}b = {@Ainv@}\times {@y@}={@ta1@}\).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
